column13: There were many things: 1.  I just wanted to say thanks for the dedication to collecting survey data and then implementing it.  I love how transparent you all are about this.   2. You set up most if not all activities to have processing time first.  This is great for introverts and just as a way for everyone to collect their thoughts before sharing out. 3. column14: I think there were two main things; 1. directions were sometimes unclear or confusing. 2. The pacing somehow felt off today. While I understand why modeling the MLR had to happen, it felt like we had basically just done that specific one after the previous model. So for the future, perhaps choosing a very different MLR to model might help.  Also, I get frustrated when the times change after we are sent to breakout rooms.  I get it that you need to make everything fit.  Our group had budgeted the time according to the original times we were given.  I totally understand making changes before we are sent  to breakout rooms, but as a result three members didn't get to share and I felt badly. Finally, I'm wondering if there is a way to "pep" things up especially when we hit the 2:30/3:00 mark. I know this is a lot and I want to make sure everyone knows the session was still great.  These are just the ideas I had.

column12: I felt like there was a disconnect with the Towers of Hanoi lesson.  As a student, I was asked to come up with a strategy to solve it in as few moves as possible.  We never really determined a solid strategy.  Furthermore, it was later revealed that the number of moves required could come from the equation  total moves = (2^n)-1 .   When shown the formula it was very briefly mentioned that number of moves was growing exponentially and that is where the equation came from.  Students were not asked to do any "heavy lifting" to come up with the formula and it actually wasn't even explained how the "teacher" came up with the (2^n)-1.  Also, later on during the number talks, somebody gave a wrong answer and the facilitator did not seem to notice and just moved on which would confuse students trying to formulate a solid understanding.

column12: This was an extremely frustrating day. I have used IM for 2 years now. At least half of us in the group have already gone through district/IM facilitator-led training. I had hoped that there would be some new information/learning that I could take away from today, but it was very minimal. Mostly gotten from talking with colleagues from different schools. Directions really need to be written out clearly. And tasks need to be fully explained.
